message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The lack of fetal cardiac activity or movement at 22 weeks gestation indicates fetal demise. Missed abortion refers to a nonviable fetus that has not been expelled, incomplete abortion is when some but not all products of conception are expelled, and ectopic pregnancy refers to a fertilized egg implanting outside the uterus.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. A lack of fetal cardiac activity and movement on two separate ultrasounds suggests fetal demise. Missed abortion and incomplete abortion involve vaginal bleeding and/or cramping, which the patient denies. Ectopic pregnancy involves implantation of the embryo outside the uterus, which is not indicated by the ultrasound findings.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The lack of fetal cardiac activity and movement on both ultrasounds suggest fetal demise. Missed abortion is the failure of the body to expel fetal tissue after fetal demise. Incomplete abortion involves the incomplete expulsion of fetal and placental tissue. Ectopic pregnancies occur when the fertilized egg implants outside of the uterus.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The absence of fetal cardiac activity and movement on ultrasound suggests fetal demise, which means the fetus has died in utero. Missed abortion refers to a situation where there is a nonviable embryo or fetus present in the uterus, but the pregnancy hormone levels remain high and the mother does not go into labor. Incomplete abortion refers to a situation where some of the products of conception have been passed, but some remain in the uterus, causing bleeding and cramps. Ectopic pregnancy refers to a pregnancy that occurs outside the uterus, most commonly in the fallopian tube.

Missed abortion and incomplete abortion both involve vaginal bleeding and/or cramping, which the patient denies. Ectopic pregnancy involves fetal development outside of the uterus, which is not consistent with the patient's presentation.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The lack of fetal cardiac activity and movement on ultrasound and repeated scans confirm fetal demise. Missed abortion would have shown signs of fetal demise on a previous ultrasound, which was not reported. Incomplete abortion and ectopic pregnancy do not match the presentation.

Missed abortion and incomplete abortion both involve incomplete or delayed expulsion of the products of conception, but in this case, there is no evidence of incomplete expulsion. Ectopic pregnancy refers to implantation of the fertilized egg outside of the uterus, which is not likely in this case as the patient has been regularly scheduled for obstetrician visit with no indication of such.

Missed abortion refers to a nonviable pregnancy that does not pass out of the uterus spontaneously, but there is no fetal movement. Incomplete abortion is characterized by vaginal bleeding and cramping, but there is no mention of these symptoms in the scenario. Ectopic pregnancy occurs when the fertilized egg implants outside the uterus, which is not the case here as fetal demise was detected on ultrasound.
